1 AN ACT
2 RELATING TO CRIME; ELIMINATING THE STATUTE OF LIMITATIONS FOR
3 CERTAIN SEXUAL CRIMES; MAKING CONFORMING AMENDMENTS.
4
5 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF NEW MEXICO:
6 SECTION 1. Section 30-1-8 NMSA 1978 (being Laws 1963,
7 Chapter 303, Section 1-8, as amended) is amended to read:
8 "30-1-8. TIME LIMITATIONS FOR COMMENCING
9 PROSECUTION.--A person shall not be prosecuted, tried or
10 punished in any court of this state unless the indictment is
11 found or information or complaint is filed within the time as
12 provided:
13 A. except as provided in Subsection H of this
14 section:
15 (1) for a second degree felony, within six
16 years from the time the crime was committed; and
17 (2) for a third or fourth degree felony,
18 within five years from the time the crime was committed;
19 B. for a misdemeanor, within two years from the
20 time the crime was committed;
21 C. for a petty misdemeanor, within one year from
22 the time the crime was committed;
23 D. for any crime against or violation of Section
24 51-1-38 NMSA 1978, within three years from the time the crime
25 was committed; SJC/SB 41
Page 1

1 E. for a felony pursuant to Section 7-1-71.3,
2 7-1-72 or 7-1-73 NMSA 1978, within five years from the time
3 the crime was committed; provided that for a series of crimes
4 involving multiple filing periods within one calendar year,
5 the limitation shall begin to run on December 31 of the year
6 in which the crimes occurred;
7 F. for an identity theft crime pursuant to Section
8 30-16-24.1 NMSA 1978, within five years from the time the
9 crime was discovered;
10 G. for any crime not contained in the Criminal
11 Code or where a limitation is not otherwise provided for,
12 within three years from the time the crime was committed; and
13 H. no limitation period shall exist and
14 prosecution for the following crimes may commence at any time
15 after the occurrence of:
16 (1) a capital felony, as provided in Section
17 31-18-14 NMSA 1978;
(2) a first degree violent felony;
18
(3) second degree murder, as provided in
19
Subsection B of Section 30-2-1 NMSA 1978;
20
(4) second degree criminal sexual contact of
21
a minor, as provided in Section 30-9-13 NMSA 1978; or
22
(5) second degree criminal sexual
23
penetration, as provided in Section 30-9-11 NMSA 1978.”
24
SECTION 2. Section 30-1-9.1 NMSA 1978 (being Laws 1987,
25 SJC/SB 41
Page 2

1 Chapter 117, Section 1) is amended to read:
2 "30-1-9.1. OFFENSES AGAINST CHILDREN--ALLEGED
3 VIOLATIONS FOR THE ABANDONMENT OR ABUSE OF A CHILD--TOLLING OF
4 STATUTE OF LIMITATIONS.--The applicable time period for
5 commencing prosecution pursuant to Section 30-1-8 NMSA 1978
6 shall not commence to run for an alleged violation of
7 abandonment or abuse of a child, as provided in Section 30-6-1
8 NMSA 1978, a third or fourth degree felony as provided in
9 Section 30-9-11 NMSA 1978 or a third or fourth degree felony
10 as provided in Section 30-9-13 NMSA 1978 until the victim
11 attains the age of eighteen or the violation is reported to a
12 law enforcement agency, whichever occurs first."
13 SECTION 3. Section 30-1-9.2 NMSA 1978 (being Laws 2003,
14 Chapter 257, Section 1) is amended to read:
15 "30-1-9.2. CRIMINAL SEXUAL PENETRATION--TOLLING OF
16 STATUTE OF LIMITATIONS.--
17 A. When DNA evidence is available and a suspect
has not been identified, the applicable time period for
18
commencing a prosecution pursuant to Section 30-1-8 NMSA 1978
19
shall not commence to run for an alleged violation of a third
20
or fourth degree felony pursuant to Section 30-9-11 NMSA 1978
21
until a DNA profile is matched with a suspect.
22
B. As used in this section, "DNA" means
23
24 deoxyribonucleic acid." SJC/SB 41
